Remarks: Same male as in XC489615 to XC489617 (where date incorrectly stated to be 19 July and time of day also wrong). The bird was singing c. 20 m above ground in a tall emergent very close to the main clearing around the laboratories and volunteer dormitories. Locality: Yard, Boca del Drago, Isla Colon, Bocas del Toro
file.name: XC498499-BellBird Sept21 2019.mp3
Remarks: Some background vocalizations of other species was lessened. Tropical lowland forest of Bocas archipelago. Adult male lekking. Procnias tricarunculatus come to Isla Colon typically in late May / early June and sometimes persist until early December. They migrate here from higher elevations for the purpose of nesting. We see many males but have only observed 3 females since living here for 12 years. A lek usually consists of 3 birds. They ave been using trees over our driveway for 5 months.

Locality: Children's Eternal Rain Forest Bajo del Tigre
file.name: XC332147-Twbe 50' Ben 1130amp.mp3
Remarks: Costa Rican dialect.  Singing from a perch in the mid canopy about 50ft from me.  Probably 3 to 4 other Bellbirds countersinging in the vicinity, some can be heard in the background.  Alternated singing with preening.  Sometimes singing was directed in my direction, other times it would face the opposite way and sing.  Adult male plumage.

file.name: XC331252-Twbe song 40' CC 1130 mp3 c.mp3
Remarks: Adult male singing Panamanian dialect from the mid-canopy about 100m off the trail and about 15m off the ground.  Switched perches a few times but seemed mostly unperturbed by our presence.  This was one of about half a dozen birds singing in the area at the time and the only one singing this particular dialect.

Remarks: Secondary forest on our property. Bird lekking in fruiting 'hobo' tree (yellow fruit size of large grape). Juvenile bird; similar to markings of female with much streaking.
